Ford GoBike System Data Exploration¶

Akolade Sofiyyah Iwalewa¶

Introduction¶

The ford gobike system dataset includes information about individual rides made in a bike-sharing system covering the greater San Francisco Bay area.

QUESTION(S) FOR ANALYSIS¶

  • What is the proportion of the gender among the users?
  • What is the proportion of user type among the users?
  • What's the bike sharing behaviour among the users?
  • How is the age of the users distributed in the dataset?
  • At what hour do users mostly start their trip?
  • Which of the days do users use bikes the most?
  • Which of the month do users mostly use bike the most?
  • How long do users go for their trips?
  • What stations are used most?
  • How often do users take trips in the month?
  • What is the average distance taken by age group?
  • What is the average distance taken by User type?
  • What's the trip distance by age group and User type?
  • What's the average duration and distance of trips by Gender, User type and Age group?

DATA QUALITY ISSUES¶

Below are all the quality issues observed

  • Null values in the following columns: start_station_id, start_station_name, end_station_id and end_station_name columns.
  • Inappropiate member_birth_year values between 1878.0 and 1938.0 and nan values
  • Incorrect datatypes for the following columns: start_time, end_time, start_station_id, end_station_id, bike_id, member_birth_year.

DATA TIDINESS ISSUES¶

Below are all the tideness issues observed

  • There should be different columns for the following: start and end time, day and month columns.
  • The member_birth_year should be the member's age not their birth year.
  • The duration_sec should be in hours.
  • Trip distance column should be calculated.

# Defining a function that calculates the distance between coordinates

def distance_calc(df_copy):
    ''' Calculates the distance between coordinates'''
    start_coordinate = (df_copy['start_station_latitude'], df_copy['start_station_longitude'])
    end_coordinate = (df_copy['end_station_latitude'], df_copy['end_station_longitude'])
    return distance.distance(start_coordinate, end_coordinate).km

# Creating the distance column
df_copy['station_distance_km'] = df_copy.apply(distance_calc, axis=1)

Comments on the cleaned dataset¶

There are 174761 records of bike trips covering the greater San Francisco Bay area for Febuary 2019, and 27 varaibles was taken into consideration. For this dataset I am interested in figuring out what features are best for predicting the period and how often bikes are rented in the City. The following features will help support my investigation in my features of intrest.

  • Time and duration of rent.
  • Age group and gender of users.
  • Origin and Destination stations of trips.

# Defining a function that calculates proportions of values in a column.

def prop_(x):
    
    #x will be df.col or df['col']
    max_var_count = x.value_counts()[0]
    var_sum = x.value_counts().sum()
    max_prop = max_var_count/var_sum
    tick_props = np.arange(0,max_prop+0.05, 0.05)
    tick_names = ['{:0.2f}'.format(v) for v in tick_props]
    
    return [tick_props, tick_names, var_sum]

Conclusions¶

  • The male gender and subscribers has the largeest amount of the Users.

  • Most of the Users are aged between 25-35.

  • The most used Stations are located around Market Street. This street is a hub of activities in San Francisco.

  • The peak time for rides are around office time, 8AM in the morning, and close time, 5PM in the evening. Also there are low number of trips during weekends.

  • As sharing trips is an option for users, only few subscribers do share trips. No customer does that.

  • On average, Customers spend more hours on trips compared to Subscribers (This amounts for about 80% of the trips)

  • Female users spend more time on trips and also take longer trips compared to Males.
